00:00:16,120 --> 00:00:18,700
Mathematical interlude is again about linear algebra,

5
00:00:18,700 --> 00:00:19,940
about vector spaces,

6
00:00:20,340 --> 00:00:21,900
but about the idea of operators.

7
00:00:21,900 --> 00:00:23,480
But before we do,

8
00:00:23,480 --> 00:00:25,820
before we get to operators,

9
00:00:25,820 --> 00:00:28,220
I want to say a few more things about vectors.

10
00:00:28,220 --> 00:00:31,720
A few more bits about the mathematics of vectors.

11
00:00:32,460 --> 00:00:35,900
Most of these bits have to do not

12
00:00:35,900 --> 00:00:39,340
so much with deep mathematics as with good notation.

13
00:00:39,700 --> 00:00:43,980
Good notation is worth an awful lot when you can

14
00:00:43,980 --> 00:00:48,260
just manipulate symbols in ways that are sort of prearranged

15
00:00:48,260 --> 00:00:52,000
and do it easily and comfortably.

16
00:00:52,650 --> 00:00:54,440
There's an enormous benefit in that.

17
00:00:54,520 --> 00:00:55,800
For doing things like this,

18
00:00:55,820 --> 00:00:57,700
you can do things like abstract mathematics,

19
00:00:57,700 --> 00:00:58,400
certainly,

20
00:00:58,580 --> 00:01:00,320
but also the abstractions,

21
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:01,960
the mathematical abstractions of physics.

22
00:01:03,519 --> 00:01:05,059
The abstractions that we're going to

23
00:01:05,059 --> 00:01:06,600
talk about are largely due to Dirac,

24
00:01:06,600 --> 00:01:07,460
Paul Dirac,

25
00:01:08,079 --> 00:01:10,179
who really was the one who saw into

26
00:01:10,179 --> 00:01:12,280
the way that quantum mechanics really fits together.

27
00:01:13,300 --> 00:01:14,720
So let's talk about that.

28
00:01:15,060 --> 00:01:17,140
We have a space of states.

29
00:01:17,140 --> 00:01:18,160
The space of states,

30
00:01:18,160 --> 00:01:20,140
which we'll come back to,

31
00:01:20,699 --> 00:01:21,140
is,

32
00:01:21,140 --> 00:01:21,800
as I said,

33
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:23,100
a linear vector space,

34
00:01:23,100 --> 00:01:25,800
meaning to say that you can multiply states,

35
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:26,620
by numbers,

36
00:01:26,620 --> 00:01:28,220
to get new states,

37
00:01:28,220 --> 00:01:30,000
and these are abstract vectors.

38
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:31,900
Abstract vectors,

39
00:01:31,900 --> 00:01:34,290
maybe I throw too much in

40
00:01:34,290 --> 00:01:36,680
when I say space of states,

41
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:38,060
just abstract vectors,

42
00:01:38,060 --> 00:01:39,840
you can multiply them by numbers,

43
00:01:39,840 --> 00:01:41,300
in our case complex numbers,

44
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:43,100
and you can add them,

45
00:01:43,100 --> 00:01:45,700
and there are two kinds of vectors.

46
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:47,680
There are the Bra vectors and the ket vectors.

47
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:48,000
They're,

48
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:48,620
roughly speaking,

49
00:01:48,620 --> 00:01:50,800
related by complex conjugation,

50
00:01:52,620 --> 00:01:54,800
and a vector space has a dimensionality.

51
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:57,810
The dimensionality is the maximum number of orthogonal

52
00:01:57,810 --> 00:02:00,820
vectors that you can find in that space,

53
00:02:01,140 --> 00:02:02,720
and once you know what

54
00:02:02,720 --> 00:02:04,300
the dimension of the space is,

55
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:06,520
you can look for a basis of vectors.

56
00:02:06,700 --> 00:02:09,669
The basis of vectors is

57
00:02:09,669 --> 00:02:12,640
a mutually orthogonal collection of normalized,

58
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:14,120
get the terminology down,

59
00:02:14,120 --> 00:02:16,260
orthonormal basis.

60
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:19,400
Ortho means that they're all orthogonal to each other.

61
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:20,720
Normal,

62
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:23,240
the word normal means normalized,

63
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:25,390
and normalized simply means that

64
00:02:25,390 --> 00:02:27,540
the vectors are of unit length.

65
00:02:30,260 --> 00:02:32,640
A collection of them that is maximal,

66
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:33,480
in other words,

67
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:34,420
that you can't find anymore,

68
00:02:34,540 --> 00:02:36,000
because there are no more directions left,

69
00:02:36,220 --> 00:02:37,680
that defines a basis,

70
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:39,390
and the number of them is

71
00:02:39,390 --> 00:02:41,100
equal to the dimensionality of the space.

72
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:42,920
Given such a basis,

73
00:02:42,920 --> 00:02:44,380
you can make,

74
00:02:44,380 --> 00:02:46,700
you can write any vector in the space

75
00:02:47,240 --> 00:02:50,560
as some kind of sum over those basis vectors.

76
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:51,720
So,

77
00:02:51,720 --> 00:02:53,220
we can write for any vector in the space,

78
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:53,560
vector A,

79
00:02:53,560 --> 00:02:57,900
that it's equal to sum over I.

80
00:02:58,100 --> 00:03:01,040
I here stands for the basis vectors.

81
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:02,460
Of course,

82
00:03:02,460 --> 00:03:04,360
a basis is not a unique thing.

83
00:03:04,980 --> 00:03:07,270
Just as there are many sets

84
00:03:07,270 --> 00:03:09,560
of mutually orthogonal vectors in three-dimensional space,

85
00:03:09,780 --> 00:03:12,840
there are many sets of mutually

86
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:15,900
orthogonal vectors in an abstract vector space,

87
00:03:16,100 --> 00:03:16,740
but we pick one.

88
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,300
We pick a set.

89
00:03:18,640 --> 00:03:19,920
Having picked that set,

90
00:03:19,920 --> 00:03:20,860
and we label it I,

91
00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:22,300
we can,

92
00:03:23,240 --> 00:03:24,870
we can write any vector

93
00:03:24,870 --> 00:03:26,500
as a sum alpha sub I,

94
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:30,460
exactly those alphas which we referred to a moment ago.

95
00:03:30,980 --> 00:03:32,040
Alpha sub I,

96
00:03:32,040 --> 00:03:33,500
a set of complex numbers,

97
00:03:33,500 --> 00:03:34,880
a set of complex coefficients,

98
00:03:35,620 --> 00:03:37,480
times the ith basis vector.

99
00:03:37,780 --> 00:03:38,840
The ith basis vector,

100
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:46,200
I'm labeling I.

101
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:48,700
This is a ket representation,

102
00:03:49,340 --> 00:03:51,180
but now what we can do with this

103
00:03:51,180 --> 00:03:53,820
is we can take the inner product with it.

104
00:03:53,880 --> 00:03:57,400
I want to try to calculate these alpha sub I's

105
00:03:57,400 --> 00:03:59,290
in terms of some

106
00:03:59,290 --> 00:04:01,180
quantities involving the vectors themselves.

107
00:04:02,160 --> 00:04:02,580
Alright,

108
00:04:02,580 --> 00:04:04,420
so what we do is we take the

109
00:04:04,420 --> 00:04:06,260
inner product of both sides of the equation

110
00:04:07,140 --> 00:04:09,220
with the basis vector J,

111
00:04:09,959 --> 00:04:11,120
the ket vector J.

112
00:04:11,340 --> 00:04:12,780
On the left-hand side,

113
00:04:12,780 --> 00:04:14,180
we get the inner product

114
00:04:15,079 --> 00:04:17,019
of the vector A,

115
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:20,740
which is the thing we're trying to express.

116
00:04:21,300 --> 00:04:23,440
And that's equal to the sum over I,

117
00:04:24,120 --> 00:04:25,200
alpha sub I,

118
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:27,860
times the inner product of the vector J,

119
00:04:28,140 --> 00:04:29,180
with the vector I.

120
00:04:31,060 --> 00:04:32,630
But the inner product of the

121
00:04:32,630 --> 00:04:34,200
vector J with this vector I

122
00:04:34,980 --> 00:04:36,520
is either 1 or 0.

123
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:40,380
It's 1 if I and J are the same vector,

124
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:41,900
and it's 0 otherwise.

125
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:43,080
Why?

126
00:04:43,080 --> 00:04:46,020
Because they're orthogonal if I is not equal to J,

127
00:04:46,220 --> 00:04:47,640
and they're normalized,

128
00:04:47,640 --> 00:04:49,300
namely of unit length,

129
00:04:49,400 --> 00:04:50,480
if I does equal J.

130
00:04:52,060 --> 00:04:52,580
So,

131
00:04:52,580 --> 00:04:54,580
this bracket over here,

132
00:04:54,700 --> 00:04:56,780
this product of bras and kets,

133
00:04:56,920 --> 00:04:59,960
is just the Kronecker symbol delta Jk,

134
00:05:00,500 --> 00:05:01,020
sorry,

135
00:05:01,020 --> 00:05:01,980
delta J I,

136
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:04,160
0 or 1,

137
00:05:04,340 --> 00:05:05,800
and when you do the sum,

138
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,080
it just picks out one and only one contribution,

139
00:05:09,380 --> 00:05:12,340
the contribution in which I is equal to J.

140
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:13,480
So,

141
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:14,860
on the right-hand side,

142
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:16,440
you just get alpha J.

143
00:05:16,860 --> 00:05:17,720
No sum.

144
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:19,640
The sum is collapsed to one term,

145
00:05:19,640 --> 00:05:24,220
and that's now equal to J A.

146
00:05:24,740 --> 00:05:25,260
Alright,

147
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:26,060
so what have we learned?

148
00:05:26,160 --> 00:05:28,080
We've learned that the coefficient here,

149
00:05:29,140 --> 00:05:31,120
in the expansion of any vector,

150
00:05:31,180 --> 00:05:36,400
is just the inner product of the Jth vector

151
00:05:36,400 --> 00:05:37,980
with the target vector,

152
00:05:38,080 --> 00:05:39,500
with the vector we're trying to describe.

153
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:44,880
The fact that I wrote a J there is irrelevant.

154
00:05:48,140 --> 00:05:49,620
It could also be alpha J.

155
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:52,380
It doesn't matter which I or which J.

156
00:05:55,640 --> 00:05:59,280
The Ith coefficient is an inner product.

157
00:05:59,620 --> 00:06:00,100
Now,

158
00:06:00,100 --> 00:06:03,160
I can use that to rewrite the sum up here.

159
00:06:03,420 --> 00:06:05,780
I now know what the alpha sub I's are.

160
00:06:06,160 --> 00:06:07,420
They're these guys over here.

161
00:06:07,880 --> 00:06:08,360
So,

162
00:06:08,360 --> 00:06:09,400
let's rewrite this.

163
00:06:10,219 --> 00:06:11,620
Sum over I.

164
00:06:12,420 --> 00:06:14,680
I'm going to start with alpha I.

165
00:06:15,400 --> 00:06:15,880
Sorry,

166
00:06:15,880 --> 00:06:16,460
with I.

167
00:06:17,180 --> 00:06:19,020
And then write alpha sub I.

168
00:06:19,620 --> 00:06:20,710
I'm going to write alpha sub

169
00:06:20,710 --> 00:06:21,800
I next to it over here

170
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:22,700
in the opposite order.

171
00:06:22,920 --> 00:06:23,960
That's allowed.

172
00:06:26,999 --> 00:06:28,560
Nothing noncommutative at this stage.

173
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:30,640
Now I want to write alpha sub I.

174
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:31,220
So,

175
00:06:31,220 --> 00:06:34,540
I write I A.

176
00:06:38,040 --> 00:06:39,340
That's a basic formula

177
00:06:40,939 --> 00:06:44,060
that any vector can be rewritten

178
00:06:44,060 --> 00:06:47,900
in terms of its coefficients

179
00:06:47,900 --> 00:06:49,600
or in terms of its inner product

180
00:06:49,620 --> 00:06:50,960
with the basis vectors

181
00:06:51,820 --> 00:06:53,720
times the basis vectors themselves.

182
00:06:54,540 --> 00:06:55,480
Summed over I.

183
00:06:55,680 --> 00:06:56,840
It's kind of a pretty formula.

184
00:06:57,540 --> 00:07:00,440
And it comes back over and over again.

185
00:07:01,120 --> 00:07:03,660
What it says is whenever you see this summation

186
00:07:04,240 --> 00:07:06,640
of I times I in that form,

187
00:07:06,920 --> 00:07:08,520
you can sort of throw it away.

188
00:07:08,860 --> 00:07:10,440
It's just A equals A.

189
00:07:10,980 --> 00:07:14,740
But it's an expression for a vector

190
00:07:14,740 --> 00:07:16,180
in terms of its components.

191
00:07:17,560 --> 00:07:18,260
All right.

192
00:07:18,260 --> 00:07:20,280
So that's one simple fact.

193
00:07:20,480 --> 00:07:23,040
The same thing is true for bra vectors.

194
00:07:24,280 --> 00:07:26,740
Exactly the same thing is true for bra vectors.

195
00:07:26,820 --> 00:07:28,660
And you would write it in the following form.

196
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:33,960
A bra vector is also a sum over I

197
00:07:33,960 --> 00:07:40,820
of the inner product of the bra vector

198
00:07:40,820 --> 00:07:43,060
with the basis vectors

199
00:07:44,059 --> 00:07:46,440
times the basis bra vectors.

200
00:07:46,440 --> 00:07:49,920
The basis bra vectors are just the complex conjugates,

201
00:07:49,940 --> 00:07:50,360
if you like,

202
00:07:50,360 --> 00:07:53,440
of the basis ket vectors.

203
00:07:53,820 --> 00:07:55,500
Both of these equations are true.

204
00:07:55,640 --> 00:07:58,280
And we're going to find out that they're enormously useful.

205
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:03,400
They're enormously useful and powerful,

206
00:08:03,700 --> 00:08:05,280
even though they were very,

207
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:05,840
very simple.

208
00:08:07,220 --> 00:08:07,940
All right.

209
00:08:07,960 --> 00:08:10,300
Now we come to the notion of linear operators.

210
00:08:11,520 --> 00:08:14,300
States in quantum mechanics are vectors.

211
00:08:15,480 --> 00:08:18,240
And we saw a little bit about how that works

212
00:08:18,920 --> 00:08:20,820
in the case of a single spin.

213
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:22,920
Observables.

214
00:08:23,420 --> 00:08:25,780
Observables mean the things that we measure.

215
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:27,920
The things that we measure,

216
00:08:27,960 --> 00:08:29,180
the objects that we measure,

217
00:08:29,220 --> 00:08:30,460
the quantities that we measure.

218
00:08:30,820 --> 00:08:33,929
The observables are related to

219
00:08:33,929 --> 00:08:37,039
linear operators in the space.

220
00:08:37,580 --> 00:08:38,240
All right.

221
00:08:38,280 --> 00:08:39,539
So what is a linear operator?

222
00:08:41,020 --> 00:08:43,559
And it'll take us the rest of the evening

223
00:08:43,559 --> 00:08:44,280
to understand that.

224
00:08:44,280 --> 00:08:45,680
And in any detail what

225
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:47,080
it has to do with observables.

226
00:08:47,620 --> 00:08:49,740
So put that out of your head for the moment.

227
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:51,940
We're just doing a mathematical interlude now.

228
00:08:52,300 --> 00:08:54,400
What is the notion of a linear operator?

229
00:08:56,060 --> 00:09:01,500
A linear operator is a process,

230
00:09:01,500 --> 00:09:02,240
if you like,

231
00:09:03,079 --> 00:09:04,940
which you apply to vectors.

232
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:07,380
Somebody or other,

233
00:09:07,380 --> 00:09:08,620
I can't remember who it might have been,

234
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:09,180
John Wheeler,

235
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:11,840
liked to describe these things as machines.

236
00:09:12,820 --> 00:09:13,820
He would say,

237
00:09:14,500 --> 00:09:17,980
a linear operator is a machine

238
00:09:17,980 --> 00:09:21,460
with two little ports in it.

239
00:09:21,800 --> 00:09:24,400
Into one port you put an input vector,

240
00:09:24,580 --> 00:09:26,120
and then you turn the wheel,

241
00:09:26,280 --> 00:09:28,120
and out comes an output vector.

242
00:09:28,620 --> 00:09:32,600
So it's a thing which acts on an input vector

243
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:33,880
to give an output vector.

244
00:09:35,040 --> 00:09:40,700
So let's call m a linear operator.

245
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:44,140
Linear is a linear we'll come to.

246
00:09:44,280 --> 00:09:46,200
So far we're just talking about operator.

247
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:47,340
A machine.

248
00:09:47,640 --> 00:09:48,720
In goes one end,

249
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:50,020
out comes another end.

250
00:09:50,420 --> 00:09:52,040
And we'll talk about what it means

251
00:09:52,040 --> 00:09:53,660
for it to be linear in a minute.

252
00:09:54,080 --> 00:09:54,640
Alright,

253
00:09:54,640 --> 00:09:56,980
so m is some operator.

254
00:09:57,640 --> 00:10:00,940
And that means that given any vector,

255
00:10:02,480 --> 00:10:04,300
when m acts on it,

256
00:10:04,300 --> 00:10:05,960
it simply gives another vector.

257
00:10:07,540 --> 00:10:08,100
Unique.

258
00:10:09,360 --> 00:10:10,440
Given any a,

259
00:10:10,440 --> 00:10:11,720
it gives a unique b.

260
00:10:13,700 --> 00:10:14,260
Unique.

261
00:10:14,260 --> 00:10:14,580
It does not mean,

262
00:10:14,580 --> 00:10:16,380
the converse may not be,

263
00:10:16,440 --> 00:10:16,780
converse,

264
00:10:16,780 --> 00:10:17,120
opposite,

265
00:10:17,120 --> 00:10:17,540
I don't know,

266
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:18,660
may not be true.

267
00:10:18,860 --> 00:10:21,470
It may not be that

268
00:10:21,470 --> 00:10:24,080
given a b on this side,

269
00:10:24,240 --> 00:10:26,160
that there's only one unique a

270
00:10:26,160 --> 00:10:28,080
that gives rise to that b.

271
00:10:29,199 --> 00:10:31,129
But it is true that

272
00:10:31,129 --> 00:10:33,060
m applied to any vector a

273
00:10:33,060 --> 00:10:35,620
gives a unique reflection of a,

274
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:39,820
which is the process m acting on a.

275
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:42,070
Now what does it mean for

276
00:10:42,070 --> 00:10:43,420
m to be a linear operator?

277
00:10:44,260 --> 00:10:44,720
Well,

278
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:46,280
first of all,

279
00:10:46,280 --> 00:10:52,640
m can act on z times a,

280
00:10:52,840 --> 00:10:55,180
where z times a is a vector.

281
00:10:56,260 --> 00:10:57,140
In fact,

282
00:10:57,140 --> 00:11:01,160
let's write that m can act on z times a.

283
00:11:01,220 --> 00:11:03,100
Z times a is itself a vector,

284
00:11:03,220 --> 00:11:05,770
because you're allowed to

285
00:11:05,770 --> 00:11:08,320
multiply vectors by complex numbers.

286
00:11:08,700 --> 00:11:10,120
Z is a complex number.

287
00:11:10,969 --> 00:11:12,800
The rule about linear operators,

288
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:17,520
is if they apply on constants times a vector,

289
00:11:17,660 --> 00:11:20,560
they just give back the constant times

290
00:11:20,560 --> 00:11:23,460
what they would have given on a.

291
00:11:25,240 --> 00:11:27,100
So it just means that a z,

292
00:11:27,100 --> 00:11:28,860
a complex number,

293
00:11:29,569 --> 00:11:32,520
a complex number can be brought through m.

294
00:11:33,510 --> 00:11:35,725
m acting on twice a gives twice

295
00:11:35,725 --> 00:11:37,940
what m would have given on a.

296
00:11:38,100 --> 00:11:40,440
m acting on three times a gives three

297
00:11:40,440 --> 00:11:42,780
times what a would have given on a.

298
00:11:42,780 --> 00:11:43,480
m gives on a.

299
00:11:44,020 --> 00:11:46,620
m acting on i times a,

300
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:49,040
the complex number of i just gives

301
00:11:49,040 --> 00:11:51,280
i times whatever m would give on a.

302
00:11:51,760 --> 00:11:53,720
That's the first rule about linearity.

303
00:11:54,080 --> 00:11:57,500
And the second rule about linearity is

304
00:11:58,540 --> 00:12:01,840
that if m acts on the sum of two vectors,

305
00:12:03,700 --> 00:12:05,260
a plus b,

306
00:12:08,760 --> 00:12:10,760
then what you get is just a sum

307
00:12:11,380 --> 00:12:13,280
of what the machine spit out for a

308
00:12:13,280 --> 00:12:15,180
and what the machine spit out for b.

309
00:12:15,420 --> 00:12:16,840
What the machine spits out when

310
00:12:16,840 --> 00:12:18,260
you put in a plus b

311
00:12:18,260 --> 00:12:21,060
is just the sum of what comes out

312
00:12:25,459 --> 00:12:31,060
m times a plus m times b.

313
00:12:31,240 --> 00:12:32,040
And that's it.

314
00:12:32,040 --> 00:12:33,980
That's the notion of a linear operator.

315
00:12:34,160 --> 00:12:35,280
There's no more to it than that.

316
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:42,860
Or at least that's the full

317
00:12:42,860 --> 00:12:44,960
set of rules about linear operators.

318
00:12:47,640 --> 00:12:48,890
Now let's see if we

319
00:12:48,890 --> 00:12:50,140
can be more concrete about them.

320
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:56,080
And see if we can learn to manipulate with them.

321
00:12:57,240 --> 00:13:03,180
Let's suppose that m times a equals b.

